data.description: In 1961, a small interracial band of “Freedom Riders” challenged discriminatory laws requiring separation of the races in interstate travel. They were attacked by white segregationists, who firebombed the bus. Images of the attack appeared in hundreds of newspapers, shocking the American public and spurring the Federal Government to issue regulations banning segregation in interstate travel.

data.weatherInfo: Temperatures can soar to extremes of heat and humidity in the summer and fall to a damp, wet, cold in the winter. data.description: On 27 March 1814, Major General Andrew Jackson ‘s army of 3,300 men attacked Chief Menawa’s 1,000 Red Stick Creek warriors fortified in a horseshoe shaped bend of the Tallapoosa River.  Over 800 Red Sticks died that day.  The battle ended the Creek War, resulted in a land cession of 23,000,000 acres to the United States and created a national hero of Andrew Jackson.

data.description: Little River is unique because it flows for most of its length atop Lookout Mountain in northeast Alabama. Forested uplands, waterfalls, canyon rims and bluffs, pools, boulders, and sandstone cliffs offer settings for a variety of recreational activities. data.description: The Tennessee River brought the early Native Americans and then the European settlers. For years, it frustrated those who tried to cross it or tame it. Men fought from its banks and others found power from its waters. It created a culture. It shaped a region. The region’s sites, buildings, and relics whisper tales of some of the nation’s biggest moments and how the river played a role in each.

data.description: The 450-mile foot trail that became known as the Natchez Trace was the lifeline through the Old Southwest.  You can experience portions of that journey the way earlier travelers did - on foot.  Today there are five separate trails totaling over 60 miles and they are administered by the Natchez Trace Parkway.

images.title: Potkopinu Section of the Natchez Trace National Scenic Trail
images.caption: The Potkopinu section, between milepost 17 and 20, follows the historic Old Trace. The "sunken" nature of the trail is due to the footsteps of thousands of travelers between the 1780s and 1820s in the soft loess soil.

data.description: The Natchez Trace Parkway is a 444-mile recreational road and scenic drive through three states. It roughly follows the "Old Natchez Trace" a historic travel corridor used by American Indians, "Kaintucks," European settlers, slave traders, soldiers, and future presidents. Today, people can enjoy not only a scenic drive but also hiking, biking, horseback riding, and camping along the parkway.

images.altText: Meriwether Lewis Monument on a summer day
images.title: Meriwether Lewis Monument (milepost 385.9) on the Natchez Trace Parkway
images.caption: Built in 1848, this monument commemorates the life of Meriwether Lewis of the Lewis & Clark Corps of Discovery. Lewis died near the monument while traveling the Natchez Trace in 1809. Though questions exist, most historians believe Lewis died of suicide.

images.altText: View of the Double Arch Bridge from Birdsong Hollow
images.title: Double Arch Bridge over Birdsong Hollow (milepost 438) on the Natchez Trace Parkway
images.caption: The elegant Double Arch Bridge won the Presidential Award for Design Excellence in 1995. It spans Birdsong Hollow and Tennessee Highway 96. To see it from below, take the TN 96 exit and stop at the pulloff before you get to the highway.

images.altText: Mount Locust Historic House
images.title: Mount Locust Historic House (milepost 15.5) on the Natchez Trace Parkway
images.caption: Mount Locust served as a family home and as a stand, or inn, for Natchez Trace travelers. Built around 1780, the home and grounds are open for visitors during operating hours.

images.altText: A foggy section of the Old Trace in autumn
images.title: Old Trace (milepost 221.4) on the Natchez Trace Parkway
images.caption: The "Old Trace," the historic trail commemorated by the Natchez Trace Parkway today, still survives in segments. The Old Trace was the main road through the Old Southwest, connecting Natchez to Nashville by going through Chickasaw and Choctaw lands.

images.altText: A slightly curvy section of the Natchez Trace Parkway in Early Fall
images.title: Natchez Trace Parkway in Early Fall
images.caption: The Natchez Trace Parkway commemorates a historic travel route that helped build the young United States. The Parkway 444 miles, with plenty of stops to allow you to explore some of the history or enjoy the scenery along the way.

data.description: Russell Cave is an archeological site with one of the most complete records of prehistoric cultures in the Southeast.  In the 1950s, archeologists uncovered a large quantity of artifacts representing over 10,000 years of use in a single place.  Today, Russell Cave National Monument helps bring to light many cultural developments of phenomenal human journeys.

data.description: On August 6, 1965, President Lyndon Johnson signed, the Voting Rights Act of 1965, which extended equal voting rights for African-Americans. As both White and Black non-violent supporters led by Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. fought for the right to vote in Central Alabama, today, you can trace their march toward freedom on the 54-mile trail and connect with their stories at the Interpretive Centers.

data.description: Remember and commemorate the survival of the Cherokee people, forcefully removed from their homelands in Georgia, Alabama, and Tennessee to live in Indian Territory, now Oklahoma. They traveled by foot, horse, wagon, or steamboat in 1838-1839.

images.altText: large white house, green lawn, two trees in front
images.title: Chieftain's Museum, Rome, Georgia
images.caption: The museum tells the story of Major Ridge, the influential Ridge family including prominent son John Ridge, Cherokee history, and the Trail of Tears, as well as subsequent history of the home and region.

images.altText: structure in the background with large chimney on the end; signs saying Brown's Ferry Tavern
images.title: Brown's Ferry Tavern, Chattanooga, Tennessee
images.caption: Cherokee leader John Brown, who owned 640 acres in this area, ordered the construction of Browns Ferry Tavern in 1803. In 1838, the road running past this structure was the route by which several Cherokee detachments were removed to present-day Oklahoma.

images.altText: sunlight coming through trees with green leaves
images.title: Mantle Rock Preserve, Joy, Kentucky
images.caption: Thousands of Cherokee camped for weeks along the main (northern) route, near Mantle Rock, during the winter of 1838-39 as they waited for ice conditions in the Ohio River to allow a safe crossing.

images.altText: dozens of people walk a section of the Trail of Tears, winter scene, trees with no leaves
images.title: Cherokee Retracement at Pea Ridge National Military Park, Garfield, Arkansas
images.caption: The Pea Ridge National Military Park encompasses 4,300 acres and features a visitor center, museum, self-guided tours, reconstructed Elkhorn Tavern, and a retracement trail along a 2.5-mile original route segment of the Trail of Tears.

images.altText: Two people walk a remnant of the Trail of Tears. Spring setting with green leafed trees.
images.title: Crabb Abbott Farm, Grantsburg, Illinois
images.caption: Crabb Abbott Farm has segments of the Northern Route, including the rock crossing and ford of Sugar Creek. These segments are contiguous with trail segments on the adjacent Shawnee National Forest.

images.altText: gravestone with words etched, green grass
images.title: Grave Stone of William Adair, Stilwell, Oklahoma
images.caption: When the Cherokee arrived at their prescribed disbandment depot in Oklahoma, settlements sprang up nearby. There was a depot at the Adair's farm near present-day Stilwell, Oklahoma.

data.description: Before the first African American military pilots became known as the "Red Tails" they wore striped tails as they began their flight training in the Army's PT-17 Stearman bi-plane.  Their flying adventure started at Moton Field, in Tuskegee, Alabama, where the Army Air Corps conducted a military test to determine if African Americans could be trained to fly combat aircraft.

images.altText: Red-Tail P-51D Mustang In Flight Exhibit
images.title: The "Duchess Arlene" -  flown by Robert Williams, Pilot class
images.caption: One of the most beloved and recognized airplanes of World War II -  North American P-51D Mustang

images.altText: A World War II flight simulator and PT-17 bi-wing training plane
images.title: Training Days at Tuskegee
images.caption: Take a  "Walk Back In Time" in Hangar #1 to see the faces and visit the places where cadets trained as America's first African-American military pilots and support crews.

images.altText: Female Mechanic works on military aircraft
images.title: And There Were Women...
images.caption: Many are amazed to learn of the vital role women played as part of the Tuskee "Airmen" Experience.

images.altText: Small Yellow training plane used in the Civilian Pilot Training Prograj - J3 Piper Cub
images.title: First Flight - Eleanor Roosevelt was the first First Lady to fly with a Negro Pilot.
images.caption: Visitors are surprised to see the small size of the airplane in which First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt took a flight with Negro Pilot Charles A. Anderson.

images.altText: Two airplane hangars - Hangar #1 in foreground and Hangar #2 in background at Moton Field.
images.title: History Lives at Moton Field
images.caption: Come, experience the "power of place" where the Tuskegee Airmen blazed a trail that led to the civil rights movement.of the 1950's and 1960's.

data.description: In 1881, Booker T. Washington arrived in Alabama and started building Tuskegee Institute both in reputation and literally brick by brick.  He recruited the best and the brightest to come and teach here including George Washington Carver who arrived in 1896.  Carver’s innovations in agriculture, especially with peanuts, expanded Tuskegee’s standing throughout the country.  The story continues….

images.altText: A three story Queen Anne Revival style red brick house
images.title: The Oaks - The Home of Booker T. Washington
images.caption: This house, like Washington himself, was a lesson plan to both students and benefactors of Tuskegee Institute.

images.altText: Sunset of blue, red, and orange sky behind The Oaks, Booker T. Washngton home
images.title: Sunset Over The Oaks
images.caption: As the the sun sets behind The Oaks, the beauty of the Tuskegee sky shines through.

images.altText: A  brown colored modified school bus with two windows
images.title: The Movable School
images.caption: Many are amazed to see the last Movable School that was used by Dr. George W. Carver to bring education to the rural communities surrounding Tuskegee

images.altText: George W. Carver and Henry Ford seated facing one another talking
images.title: Carver with Friend and Fellow Inventor, Henry Ford
images.caption: Millions have been impressed by the genious of George W. Carver, including Henry Ford, Founder of Ford Motor Company

images.altText: Bottle of Peanut Oil with green label - one of Dr. Carver's many uses for the peanut
images.title: Carver's Peanut Oil
images.caption: Hundreds flocked to Tuskegee for polio treatment using George W. Carver's peanut oil
